“Getting Out of the Box” is a phrase that every homeowner should be aware of. 

Recently, I was talking to my CPA ( @soldbyplaza ) , who referred to “the box” as the house that you reside in. Essentially, this means selling your home and upgrading to a new one. If you’ve purchased your primary residence in 2021 or earlier, you may want to sell your home before you end up paying up to 40% in capital gain tax.

Capital gain tax, is a tax on the profit you make from selling an asset, including your home. The capital gain is the difference between the amount you sell your home for and the original purchase price. If you have owned your primary residence for over a year, this gain will be taxed at a different rate than ordinary income. 

Feel free to check your equity by clicking the link in my bio - FREE EQUITY CHECKER 

However, if you sell your home for a profit of up to $250,000 (if single) or $500,000 (if married), you can keep that profit completely tax-free.
As your home’s value increases, so does the likelihood that you’ll exceed the tax-free profit threshold. In this case, you would need to pay capital gain tax on any amount over that limit. To avoid this, it’s important to consider selling your home and upgrading to a new one before you surpass the tax-free limit. You can use the profits from the sale to put down a larger down payment on a new home or use the funds for other investments.

If you’re thinking about “Getting Out of the Box,” now is the time to act. Don’t hesitate to contact a trusted real estate agent to help you navigate these tax implications and explore your options for upgrading.
